{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 02:28:13.067529", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nOverview\n- Overall L3 connectivity across the enterprise fabric is healthy: hosts can reach the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) with low RTT and zero packet loss.\n- Critical service-level anomaly detected: DNS resolution is failing end-to-end. This prevents name-based access to web services (web0.local…web3.local, web99.local), causing ~5s timeouts on clients. Access by IP works.\n- Load balancer and web services are reachable by IP and respond with normal latency.\n\nKey Findings\n\n1) Reachability and Routing (OSPF path health)\n- Pings: host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 can ping dns_server (10.200.0.2), load_balancer (10.200.0.7), and web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) with 0% loss and ~2–4 ms RTT. Full multi-host reachability snapshot shows consistent low-latency connectivity and no loss between sampled endpoints across areas.\n- Conclusion: Underlay L3 forwarding and OSPF advertisements for 10.200.0.0/24 are functioning.\n\n2) DNS Service (abnormal)\n- From hosts:\n  - curl to hostnames (web99.local, web0.local) shows total ~5.0 s with name lookup/connect/pretransfer/starttransfer = 0, indicating DNS timeout prior to any TCP connection.\n  - dig from hosts to 10.200.0.2 (dns_server) times out (no servers could be reached; EXIT:9).\n  - /etc/resolv.conf on both hosts points to nameserver 10.200.0.2, so they rely on this DNS.\n- On dns_server:\n  - named.service is active (running).\n  - Netstat/ss shows TCP/UDP port 53 listening on 10.200.0.2 and 127.0.0.1.\n  - However, even local queries time out (dig @127.0.0.1 ... → timeout).\n  - nftables ruleset contains drop rules for DNS in all directions:\n    - inet filter input: tcp dport 53 drop; udp dport 53 drop\n    - inet filter output: tcp dport 53 drop; udp dport 53 drop\n    - inet filter forward: tcp dport 53 drop; udp dport 53 drop\n  - This explains both local and remote DNS query failures despite named listening.\n  - BIND config (/etc/bind/named.conf + db.local) is otherwise consistent: authoritative zone “local” with A records for web0–web3 and web99 pointing to 10.200.0.x, recursion disabled (appropriate for authoritative-only).\n- Conclusion: DNS traffic is being blocked at the dns_server host firewall (nftables), causing end-to-end DNS failure.\n\n3) Web and Load Balancer Services\n- Load balancer:\n  - nginx.service is active (running).\n  - Listens on 0.0.0.0:80; HTTP tests to 10.200.0.7 from both hosts succeed with starttransfer ~0.23–0.32 s and total ~1.0–1.1 s.\n- Web servers:\n  - Systemctl shows apache2.service inactive (dead) on web_server_0–3.\n  - Despite that, port 80 is listening on all web servers (0.0.0.0:80), and HTTP by IP succeeds from both hosts with typical total 1.0–2.1 s.\n  - Observation: HTTP is being served by a different process than apache2.service (likely non-systemd managed). Functionally, the service is reachable and responsive.\n- Conclusion: HTTP services and the load balancer are operational by IP; hostname access fails only because DNS is down.\n\nAnomalies Detected\n- Primary anomaly: DNS outage. All DNS queries to/from dns_server are dropped, including loopback, due to nftables rules dropping tcp/udp dport 53 in input/output/forward chains.\n- Secondary observation (not service-impacting at this time): apache2.service inactive on web_server_0–3 while port 80 is listening; suggests HTTP provided by another server/process. No direct impact observed since HTTP responses are normal.\n\nFault Localization\n- Faulty device: dns_server\n- Faulty component: Host firewall (nftables) ruleset, inet filter chains.\n- Evidence:\n  - Host queries: dig to 10.200.0.2 from clients → timeouts.\n  - Local queries: dig @127.0.0.1 on dns_server → timeouts (despite named listening).\n  - nft list ruleset shows explicit drops on tcp/udp port 53 in input, output, and forward.\n\nRoot Cause\n- Misconfigured firewall on dns_server is dropping all DNS (TCP/UDP port 53) in both directions. This prevents the named daemon from receiving or sending DNS traffic, causing all DNS lookups to time out across the network and locally on the server.\n\nImpact Assessment\n- Users cannot resolve local zone hostnames (web0.local…web3.local, web99.local). HTTP/S by IP remains functional, but applications relying on DNS fail or experience noticeable timeouts.\n- Routing/OSPF, switching, and server IP reachability remain healthy; the issue is isolated to DNS service filtering on dns_server.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 51889, "output_tokens": 3963, "total_tokens": 55852, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 51584}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2816}}}
